680439, 3182448], 'cluster_id': 6240609, 'court': 'California Court of Appeal, 5th District', 'court_citation_string': 'Cal. Ct. App. 5th', 'court_exact': 'calctapp5d', 'court_id': 'calctapp5d', 'court_jurisdiction': None, 'dateArgued': None, 'dateFiled': '2019-07-02T00:00:00-07:00', 'dateReargued': None, 'dateReargumentDenied': None, 'date_created': '2022-01-21T08:34:46.003820-08:00', 'docketNumber': 'C082729', 'docket_id': 62615941, 'download_url': None, 'id': 6107566, 'joined_by_ids': None, 'judge': 'Hull, Mauro', 'lexisCite': '', 'local_path': None, 'neutralCite': '', 'ordering_key': 2, 'panel_ids': None, 'per_curiam': False, 'scdb_id': '', 'sibling_ids': [6107566, 6107565], 'snippet': '\nMauro, J., Concurring and Dissenting.\nI fully concur with parts I, III, IV, VI, VII, and VIII of the majority opinion, but I disagree with parts II and <mark>V</mark> addressing the electronic device search condition and the e-mail/internet search condition (hereafter the e-search conditions), which the majority opinion appears to analyze in the same manner. Although the majority opinion disagrees with the test applied in some other published opinions, I *157would reach the same result regardless of the test', 'status': 'Precedential', 'suitNature': '', 'timestamp': '2025-10-22T22:18:13.976225-07:00', 'type': '040dissent'}, {'absolute_url': '/opinion/2685461/state-v-nicolas-subdiaz-osorio/', 'attorney': "For the defendant-appellant-petitioner, there were briefs by John A. Pray and Frank J. Remington Center, University of Wisconsin Law School, and oral argument by Lanny Glinberg., For the plaintiff-respondent, the cause was argued by Daniel J. O'Brien, assistant attorney general, with whom on the brief was JB. Van Hollen, attorney general.", 'author_id': None, 'caseName': 'State v. Nicolas Subdiaz-Osorio', 'citation': ['357 Wis. 2d 41', '2014 WI 87', '2014 Wisc. LEXIS 665', '849 N.W.2d 748', '2014 WL 3634768'], 'citeCount': 1, 'cites': None, 'cluster_id': 2685461, 'court': 'Wisconsin Supreme Court', 'court_citation_string': 'Wis.', 'court_exact': 'wis', 'court_id': 'wis', 'court_jurisdiction': None, 'dateArgued': None, 'dateFiled': '2014-07-24T00:00:00-07:00', 'dateReargued': None, 'dateReargumentDenied': None, 'date_created': '2023-08-31T01:24:51.853104-07:00', 'docketNumber': '2010AP003016-CR', 'docket_id': 407089, 'download_url': None, 'id': 9800582, 'joined_by_ids': None, 'judge': 'Prosser, Bradley, Crooks, Roggensack, Ziegler, Abrahamson', 'lexisCite': '', 'local_path': None, 'neutralCite': '2014 WI 87', 'ordering_key': 5, 'panel_ids': None, 'per_curiam': False, 'scdb_id': '', 'sibling_ids': [9800580, 9800581, 9800582, 2685461, 9800578, 9800579, 9800583], 'snippet': "\nANNETTE KINGSLAND ZIEGLER, J.\n¶ 139. {concurring). I join Justice Roggensack's concurrence, but write separately to address the United States Supreme *113Court's recent decision in <mark>Riley v. California</mark>, <mark>573</mark> <mark>U.S</mark>. _, 134 S. Ct. 2473 (<mark>2014</mark>). Riley addressed whether a warrantless search of the contents of a suspect's cell by police was constitutionally permissible, id. at 2477, while in the case at issue, Subdiaz-Osorio objects to the disclosure of location data by his cell phone service provider. See", 'status': 'Precedential', 'suitNature': '', 'timestamp': '2025-10-23T15:32:31.653591-07:00', 'type': '030concurrence'}, {'absolute_url': '/opinion/7704179/state-v-phillips/', 'attorney': 'Ashley Moody, Attorney General, Tallahassee, and Kristen L. Davenport, Assistant Attorney General, Daytona Beach, for Appellant., James S. Purdy, Public Defender, and George D. E. Burden, Assistant Public Defender, Daytona Beach, for Appellee.', 'author_id': None, 'caseName': 'State v. Phillips', 'citation': ['266 So. 3d 873'], 'citeCount': 0, 'cites': None, 'cluster_id': 7704179, 'court': 'District Court of Appeal of Florida', 'court_citation_string': 'Fla. Dist. Ct. App.', 'court_exact': 'fladistctapp', 'court_id': 'fladistctapp', 'court_jurisdiction': None, 'dateArgued': None, 'dateFiled': '2019-03-22T00:00:00-07:00', 'dateReargued': None, 'dateReargumentDenied': None, 'date_created': '2022-07-29T14:01:13.484634-07:00', 'docketNumber': 'Case No. 5D17-4041', 'docket_id': 64707915, 'download_url': None, 'id': 7639633, 'joined_by_ids': None, 'judge': 'Eisnaugle', 'lexisCite': '', 'local_path': None, 'neutralCite': '', 'ordering_key': None, 'panel_ids': None, 'per_curiam': False, 'scdb_id': '', 'sibling_ids': [7639633], 'snippet': 'guarantees "[t]he right of the people to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects, against unreasonable searches and seizures." Amend. IV, <mark>U.S</mark>. Const.2 "As the text makes clear, \'the ultimate touchstone of the Fourth Amendment is reasonableness.\' " <mark>Riley v. California</mark> , <mark>573</mark> U.S. <mark>373</mark>, 381-82, 134 S.Ct. 2473, 189 L.Ed.2d 430 (<mark>2014</mark>) (quoting Brigham City v. Stuart , 547 U.S. 398, 403, 126 S.Ct. 1943, 164 L.Ed.2d 650 (2006) ). Therefore, courts generally employ a balancing test to determine', 'status': 'Precedential', 'suitNature': '', 'timestamp': '2025-10-26T16:08:38.331096-07:00', 'type': '020lead'}, {'absolute_url': '/opinion/7704180/state-v-phillips/', 'attorney': 'Ashley Moody, Attorney General, Tallahassee, and Kristen L. Davenport, Assistant Attorney General, Daytona Beach, for Appellant., James S. Purdy, Public Defender, and George D. E. Burden, Assistant Public Defender, Daytona Beach, for Appellee.', 'author_id': None, 'caseName': 'State v. Phillips', 'citation': ['266 So. 3d 873'], 'citeCount': 0, 'cites': None, 'cluster_id': 7704180, 'court': 'District Court of Appeal of Florida', 'court_citation_string': 'Fla. Dist. Ct. App.', 'court_exact': 'fladistctapp', 'court_id': 'fladistctapp', 'court_jurisdiction': None, 'dateArgued': None, 'dateFiled': '2019-03-22T00:00:00-07:00', 'dateReargued': None, 'dateReargumentDenied': None, 'date_created': '2022-07-29T14:01:13.947943-07:00', 'docketNumber': 'Case No. 5D17-4041', 'docket_id': 64707916, 'download_url': None, 'id': 7639634, 'joined_by_ids': None, 'judge': 'Eisnaugle', 'lexisCite': '', 'local_path': None, 'neutralCite': '', 'ordering_key': None, 'panel_ids': None, 'per_curiam': False, 'scdb_id': '', 'sibling_ids': [7639634], 'snippet': 'guarantees "[t]he right of the people to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects, against unreasonable searches and seizures." Amend. IV, <mark>U.S</mark>. Const.2 "As the text makes clear, \'the ultimate touchstone of the Fourth Amendment is reasonableness.\' " <mark>Riley v. California</mark> , <mark>573</mark> U.S. <mark>373</mark>, 381-82, 134 S.Ct. 2473, 189 L.Ed.2d 430 (<mark>2014</mark>) (quoting Brigham City v. Stuart , 547 U.S. 398, 403, 126 S.Ct. 1943, 164 L.Ed.2d 650 (2006) ). Therefore, courts generally employ a balancing test to determine', 'status': 'Precedential', 'suitNature': '', 'timestamp': '2025-10-26T16:08:38.337729-07:00', 'type': '020lead'}, {'absolute_url': '/opinion/4586722/pohland-v-state/', 'attorney': '\n  Cynthia L. Strout, Anchorage, for the Appellant.\n , \n  Michal Stryszak, Assistant Attorney General, Office of Criminal Appeals, Anchorage, and Jahna Lindemuth, Attorney General, Juneau, for the Appellee.\n ', 'author_id': None, 'caseName': 'Pohland v. State', 'citation': ['436 P.3d 1093'], 'citeCount': 7, 'cites': [794809, 2680439, 2743343, 4089523, 4146684, 4264677, 6798958, 9877505], 'cluster_id': 4586722, 'court': 'Court of Appeals of Alaska', 'court_citation_string': 'Alaska Ct. App.', 'court_exact': 'alaskactapp', 'court_id': 'alaskactapp', 'court_jurisdiction': None, 'dateArgued': None, 'dateFiled': '2019-02-01T00:00:00-08:00', 'dateReargued': None, 'dateReargumentDenied': None, 'date_created': '2019-02-01T10:03:28.669078-08:00', 'docketNumber': '2632 A-12443', 'docket_id': 14531096, 'download_url': 'https://public.courts.alaska.gov/web/appellate/opinions/ap-2632.pdf', 'id': 4363975, 'joined_by_ids': None, 'judge': 'Mannheimer, Allard, Wollenberg', 'lexisCite': '', 'local_path': 'pdf/2019/02/01/pohland_v._state.pdf', 'neutralCite': '', 'ordering_key': None, 'panel_ids': None, 'per_curiam': False, 'scdb_id': '', 'sibling_ids': [4363975], 'snippet': 'search of her computer was unlawful. Even when the police have a warrant to search a house, a personal computer must be treated differently from other objects or containers in the house. As the United States Supreme Court explained in\n  \n   <mark>Riley v. California</mark>\n  \n  ,\n  \n   1\n  \n  a police search of this kind of personal digital device "[will] typically expose to the government far more than the most exhaustive search of a [person\'s] house", because the device "not only contains in digital form many', 'status': 'Precedential', 'suitNature': '', 'timestamp': '2025-11-26T18:31:12.783870-08:00', 'type': '010combined'}, {'absolute_url': '/opinion/2760668/heien-v-north-carolina/', 'attorney': 'Jeffrey L. Fisher, Stanford, CA, for Petitioner., Rachel P. Kovner, for the United States as amicus curiae, by special leave of the Court, supporting the Respondent., Michele Goldman, Raleigh, NC, Donald B. Ayer, Jones Day, Washington, DC, Jeffrey L. Fisher, Counsel of Record, Stanford Law School, Supreme Court Litigation Clinic, Stanford, CA, for Petitioner., *534Roy Cooper, Attorney General of North Carolina, John F. Maddrey, Solicitor General of North Carolina, Robert C. Montgomery, Counsel of Record, Senior Deputy Attorney General, Derrick C. Mertz, Assistant Attorney General, North Carolina Department of Justice, Raleigh, NC, for Respondent.', 'author_id': None, 'caseName': 'Heien v. North Carolina', 'citation': ['190 L. Ed. 2d 475', '135 S. Ct. 530', '2014 U.S. LEXIS 8306', '83 U.S.L.W. 4021', '25 Fla. L. Weekly Fed. S 20'], 'citeCount': 600, 'cites': None, 'cluster_id': 2760668, 'court': 'Supreme Court of the United States', 'court_citation_string': 'SCOTUS', 'court_exact': 'scotus', 'court_id': 'scotus', 'court_jurisdiction': None, 'dateArgued': None, 'dateFiled': '2014-12-15T00:00:00-08:00', 'dateReargued': None, 'dateReargumentDenied': None, 'date_created': '2023-08-31T10:41:42.167459-07:00', 'docketNumber': '13–604.', 'docket_id': 2614870, 'download_url': None, 'id': 9805194, 'joined_by_ids': None, 'judge': 'Robertsdelivered, Sotomayor', 'lexisCite': '2014 U.S. LEXIS 8306', 'local_path': None, 'neutralCite': '', 'ordering_key': 2, 'panel_ids': None, 'per_curiam': False, 'scdb_id': '2014-001', 'sibling_ids': [9805193, 9805194, 2760668], 'snippet': '\nJustice SOTOMAYOR, dissenting.\nThe Court is, of course, correct that " \'the ultimate touchstone of the Fourth Amendment is "reasonableness." \' " <mark>Riley v. California</mark>,<mark>573</mark> <mark>U.S</mark>. ----, ----, 134 S.Ct. 2473, 2482, 189 L.Ed.2d 430 (<mark>2014</mark>). But this broad statement simply sets the standard a court is to apply when it conducts its inquiry into whether the Fourth Amendment has been violated. It does not define the categories of inputs that courts are to consider when assessing the reasonableness of a search', 'status': 'Precedential', 'suitNature': '', 'timestamp': '2025-10-23T15:34:07.574451-07:00', 'type': '040dissent'}, {'absolute_url': '/opinion/4897319/kavonski-desmond-waters-v-the-state-of-texas/', 'attorney': '', 'author_id': None, 'caseName': 'Kavonski Desmond Waters v. the State of Texas', 'citation': None, 'citeCount': 0, 'cites': [107423, 1355343, 1384755, 1534785, 1773615, 2407387], 'cluster_id': 4897319, 'court': 'Court of Appeals of Texas', 'court_citation_string': 'Tex. App.', 'court_exact': 'texapp', 'court_id': 'texapp', 'court_jurisdiction': None, 'dateArgued': None, 'dateFiled': '2021-06-30T00:00:00-07:00', 'dateReargued': None, 'dateReargumentDenied': None, 'date_created': '2021-07-05T00:19:04.209724-07:00', 'docketNumber': '12-19-00373-CR', 'docket_id': 60036811, 'download_url': 'http://www.search.txcourts.gov/RetrieveDocument.aspx?DocId=11268&Index=%5c%5c10%2e20%2e4%2e7%5cTamesIndexes%5ccoa12%5cOpinion', 'id': 4701098, 'joined_by_ids': None, 'judge': '', 'lexisCite': '', 'local_path': 'pdf/2021/06/30/kavonski_desmond_waters_v._the_state_of_texas.pdf', 'neutralCite': '', 'ordering_key': None, 'panel_ids': None, 'per_curiam': False, 'scdb_id': '', 'sibling_ids': [4701098], 'snippet': '                                  NO. 12-19-<mark>00373</mark>-CR\n\n                         IN THE COURT OF APPEALS\n\n              TWELFTH COURT OF APPEALS DISTRICT\n\n                                    TYLER, TEXAS\n\nKAVONSKI DESMOND WATERS,                        §      APPEAL FROM THE 420TH\nAPPELLANT\n\n<mark>V</mark>.                                              §      JUDICIAL DISTRICT COURT\n\nTHE STATE OF TEXAS,\nAPPELLEE                                        §      NACOGDOCHES COUNTY, TEXAS\n\n                           ', 'status': 'Precedential', 'suitNature': '', 'timestamp': '2025-10-22T13:09:21.791525-07:00', 'type': '010combined'}, {'absolute_url': '/opinion/4601253/united-states-v-donald-wanjiku/', 'attorney': '\n  Christopher V. Parente, Attorney, Office of the United States Attorney, Chicago, IL, for Plaintiff-Appellee.\n , \n  Joshua Herman, Attorney, Law Office of Joshua G. Herman, Chicago, IL, for Defendant-Appellant.\n , \n  Esha Bhandari, Attorney, American Civil Liberties Union, New York, NY, Amici Curiae American Civil Liberties Union Foundation, Roger Baldwin Foundation of the American Civil Liberties Union, Electronic Frontier Foundation.\n , \n  Rebecca Kim Glenberg, Attorney, Roger Baldwin Foundation of ACLU, Inc., Chicago, IL, for Amicus Curiae Roger Baldwin Foundation of the American Civil Liberties Union.\n , \n  Adam D. Schwartz, Attorney, Electronic Frontier Foundation, San Francisco, CA, for Amicus Curiae Electronic Frontier Foundation.\n ', 'author_id': 2797, 'caseName': 'United States v. Donald Wanjiku', 'citation': ['919 F.3d 472'], 'citeCount': 29, 'cites': [91573, 100567, 107729, 107979, 108332, 108841, 108845, 109675, 109714, 110959, 111262, 111509, 112608, 118030, 118036, 118474, 134729, 218926, 605565, 777268, 784403, 1400397, 2680439, 4287285], 'cluster_id': 4601253, 'court': 'Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit', 'court_citation_string': '7th Cir.', 'court_exact': 'ca7', 'court_id': 'ca7', 'court_jurisdiction': None, 'dateArgued': None, 'dateFiled': '2019-03-19T00:00:00-07:00', 'dateReargued': None, 'dateReargumentDenied': None, 'date_created': '2019-03-19T14:00:21.724003-07:00', 'docketNumber': '18-1973', 'docket_id': 14747814, 'download_url': 'http://media.ca7.uscourts.gov/cgi-bin/rssExec.pl?Submit=Display&Path=Y2019/D03-19/C:18-1973:J:Rovner:aut:T:fnOp:N:2310820:S:0', 'id': 4378506, 'joined_by_ids': None, 'judge': 'Rovner, Sykes, Barrett', 'lexisCite': '', 'local_path': 'pdf/2019/03/19/united_states_v._donald_wanjiku.pdf', 'neutralCite': '', 'ordering_key': None, 'panel_ids': None, 'per_curiam': False, 'scdb_id': '', 'sibling_ids': [4378506], 'snippet': "\n\n\n  Rovner, Circuit Judge.\n \n\n  Donald Wanjiku pled guilty to one count of transportation of child pornography in violation of 18 <mark>U.S</mark>.C. § 2252A, but he retained his right to appeal the district court's denial of his motion to suppress the primary evidence against him. That evidence included photographs and videos recovered from his cell phone, laptop and external hard drive during a warrantless border search at O'Hare International Airport. We affirm.\n \n\n\n   I.\n  \n\n\n  On June 9, 2015, Wanjiku arrived", 'status': 'Precedential', 'suitNature': 'criminal', 'timestamp': '2025-10-25T10:11:11.215858-07:00', 'type': '010combined'}, {'absolute_url': '/opinion/7335834/united-states-v-portillo-saravia/', 'attorney': "*606Richard Wesley Bennett, Financial Litigation, U.S. Attorney's Office Southern District of Texas, Houston, TX, for United States of America., Amr Adnan Ahmed, Office of the Federal Public Defender, Federal Public Defender, Houston, TX, for Jose Blademir Portillo-Saravia., Chukwudi Ifeanyi Egbuonu, Attorney at Law, Houston, TX, Houston Interpreter, for Jose Efrain Mateo.", 'author_id': None, 'caseName': 'United States v. Portillo-Saravia', 'citation': ['379 F. Supp. 3d 600'], 'citeCount': 1, 'cites': [5959, 52576, 118036, 118250, 145712, 145912, 203904, 355097, 360873, 445460, 585853, 607884, 621152, 669743, 684368, 687308, 689145, 710020, 770343, 779105, 788238, 797553, 814751, 1057180, 1189978, 2613354, 2680439, 2800860, 2973777, 2979255, 3214776, 3218715, 4164429, 4198674, 4238107, 4258139, 4299753, 7236311, 7263680, 8137990, 8474030, 9414272, 9422279, 9422515, 9423233, 9423752, 9424935, 9425606, 9427002, 9428131, 9429374, 9429728, 9429757, 9429956, 9431933, 9432823, 9433228, 9433418, 9433881, 9434181, 9434728, 9434934, 9434949, 9436658, 9477547, 9493773, 9500717, 9806947, 9842054, 9873768, 9876158, 9888364], 'cluster_id': 7335834, 'court': 'District Court, S.D. Texas', 'court_citation_string': 'S.D. Tex.', 'court_exact': 'txsd', 'court_id': 'txsd', 'court_jurisdiction': None, 'dateArgued': None, 'dateFiled': '2019-05-10T00:00:00-07:00', 'dateReargued': None, 'dateReargumentDenied': None, 'date_created': '2022-07-24T23:23:11.695301-07:00', 'docketNumber': 'CRIMINAL NO. 4:18-0650', 'docket_id': 64324321, 'download_url': None, 'id': 7253754, 'joined_by_ids': None, 'judge': 'Atlas', 'lexisCite': '', 'local_path': None, 'neutralCite': '', 'ordering_key': None, 'panel_ids': None, 'per_curiam': False, 'scdb_id': '', 'sibling_ids': [7253754], 'snippet': 'Court grants in part and denies in part both Motions to Suppress.\nI. BACKGROUND\nA. Procedural Background\nOn October 31, 2018, a federal grand jury charged Defendants Mateo and Portillo with unlawful possession of a firearm by an illegal alien.4 See 18 <mark>U.S</mark>.C. § 922(g)(5)(A).\nIn February 2019, Defendants Mateo and Portillo each filed a Motion to Suppress. Defendants contend that the Court should suppress: (1) bullets seized from their persons during a traffic stop, (2) handguns seized from the car they', 'status': 'Precedential', 'suitNature': '', 'timestamp': '2025-07-08T14:56:23.394227-07:00', 'type': '020lead'}, {'absolute_url': '/opinion/10610478/state-of-louisiana-v-christopher-rousset/', 'attorney': '', 'author_id': None, 'caseName': 'State of Louisiana v. Christopher Rousset', 'citation': None, 'citeCount': 0, 'cites': [104504, 2680439, 9424643, 9433198, 9434949, 9441559], 'cluster_id': 10610478, 'court': 'Louisiana Court of Appeal', 'court_citation_string': 'La. Ct. App.', 'court_exact': 'lactapp', 'court_id': 'lactapp', 'court_jurisdiction': None, 'dateArgued': None, 'dateFiled': '2020-06-03T00:00:00-07:00', 'dateReargued': None, 'dateReargumentDenied': None, 'date_created': '2025-06-18T08:45:59.673522-07:00', 'docketNumber': '2020-K-0202', 'docket_id': 70573062, 'download_url': 'https://www.la4th.org/opinion/2020/486551.pdf', 'id': 11077066, 'joined_by_ids': None, 'judge': '', 'lexisCite': '', 'local_path': 'pdf/2020/06/03/state_of_louisiana_v._christopher_rousset_1.pdf', 'neutralCite': '', 'ordering_key': None, 'panel_ids': None, 'per_curiam': False, 'scdb_id': '', 'sibling_ids': [11077066], 'snippet': 'Defendant’<mark>s</mark> statement that he owned the cell phone.\n\nHowever, I respectfully dissent from the majority’s finding that the district court\n\nerred in suppressing the evidence seized from the warrantless search of\n\nDefendant’s cell phone. The majority reasons the district court did not consider the\n\nvalidity of the search warrant that was ultimately obtained to search Defendant’s\n\ncell phone; and accordingly, improperly relied on <mark>Riley v. California</mark>, <mark>573</mark> <mark>U.S.</mark>\n\n<mark>373</mark>, 134 S.Ct. 2473, 189 L.Ed.2d 430 (<mark>2014</mark>), in', 'status': 'Precedential', 'suitNature': '', 'timestamp': '2025-10-27T13:38:29.623150-07:00', 'type': '035concurrenceinpart'}, {'absolute_url': '/opinion/9495665/the-state-of-texas-v-erik-rodriguez/', 'attorney': '', 'author_id